## Risk-Tiered Execution (T0–T3)

arifOS enforces proportional governance by classifying every tool action into one of four risk tiers. Overhead scales with potential impact — not with verbosity.

```yaml
risk_tiers:
  T0_INERT:
    description: "Read-only actions. No approval required. O(1) policy cache lookup."
    examples:
      - fs.read
      - git.status
      - git.log
      - memory.read
      - tool_heartbeat
    gates:
      - policy_cache_hit: skip_verification
      - no_receipt_required  # T0 does not pollute receipt DAG

  T1_REVERSIBLE:
    description: "Write actions with automatic rollback snapshot."
    examples:
      - fs.write (workspace only)
      - git.commit
      - memory.write
      - session.update
    gates:
      - pre_execute: snapshot_current_state
      - post_execute: emit_t1_receipt_with_rollback_link
      - auto_revert_if: verdict == VOID

  T2_CONTROLLED:
    description: "Higher-risk actions requiring strict policy matching."
    examples:
      - shell.exec
      - net.fetch
      - docker.run
      - tool_dispatch (cross-domain)
    gates:
      - pre_execute: verify_risk_tier == T2
      - policy_match: capability_map check
      - emit_t2_receipt: yes
      - arifos_judge review: recommended but not mandatory

  T3_IRREVERSIBLE:
    description: "High-impact actions that block until explicit F13 approval."
    examples:
      - net.post (external write)
      - fs.write (outside workspace)
      - git.push
      - docker.build
      - secret_inject
      - agent_spawn
    gates:
      - hard_stop: "T3 — requires F13 sovereign approval"
      - arifos_judge verdict must be SEAL
      - human_approval: required
      - emit_t3_receipt: yes (blocking receipt)
      - rollback_plan documented before execution

scope_escalation:
  - capability: "fs.write"
    scope: "outside_workspace"
    escalate_to: T3
    reason: "Writes outside workspace are irreversible"
  - capability: "shell.exec"
    scope: "unscoped"
    escalate_to: T3
    reason: "Unscoped shell execution is irreversible"
  - capability: "fs.write"
    pattern: "*.env"
    escalate_to: T3
    reason: "Environment files may contain secrets"
```

### Monotonic Restriction Principle (Scoped Souls)

Any delegated context or sub-process MUST be more restrictive than its parent. A child process must never escalate permissions beyond its creator's Soul.

```yaml
monotonic_restriction:
  rule: "Child Soul ≤ Parent Soul (subset, never superset)"
  enforcement:
    - capability_narrowing: "Child toolset ⊆ Parent approved capabilities"
    - additive_constraints: "Child inherits ALL parent rules, may only add new restrictive ones"
    - scope_narrowing: "Child scope ≤ Parent scope"
    - no_broadening: "Child may not request capabilities parent does not hold"
  violation_response:
    verdict: HOLD
    reason: "Scoped Soul violation — child attempted permission escalation"
    action: "Block and surface to arifos_judge"
```

### Approval Pattern Learning (APL)

A background observer tracks owner decisions to propose automation rules, reducing approval fatigue without compromising safety.

```yaml
apl:
  enabled: true
  observe: "Track approval contexts to identify automatable patterns"
  circuit_breakers:
    daily_limit: 50        # Max auto-approvals per day
    lifetime_limit: 500     # Max auto-approvals per session chain
    cooldown_seconds: 300  # Auto-approval cooldown after denial
  deny_wins: true          # Any deny rule overrides all approval rules
  promotion_threshold: 3   # Minimum confirmations before rule proposed
  examples:
    - "owner always approves email.send to *@internal.com during business_hours"
    - "owner always approves git.commit with message matching 'docs:' prefix"
```

### Receipt-Driven Truth

Every action that produces a state change MUST emit a standardized receipt. If no receipt exists, the action effectively did not happen.

```yaml
receipt_schema:
  required_fields:
    - receipt_id: "UUID — unique per action"
    - timestamp: "ISO 8601 — UTC"
    - parent_id: "UUID of parent action (null for root)"
    - tool_name: "canonical tool identifier"
    - risk_tier: "T0|T1|T2|T3"
    - soul_version: "active Soul SHA at execution time"
    - actor_id: "session or sub-agent performing action"
    - governance_trace:
        policy_used: "policy document SHA"
        risk_tier_verdict: "SEAL|CAUTION|HOLD|VOID"
        gates_passed: ["list of gate names"]
    - outcome: "success|error|blocked|rolled_back"
    - redacted_inputs: "sanitized — passwords/tokens stripped before log"
  optional_fields:
    - rollback_link: "receipt_id of pre-execute snapshot (T1/T2)"
    - latency_ms: "execution duration"
    - entropy_delta: "thermodynamic delta caused by this action"
  storage: "vault_postgres — receipts table"
  retention: "immutable — no DELETE, no UPDATE after commit"
  dag_integrity: "parent_id creates verifiable action chain"
```

### Deterministic Context Compilation (Memory Budgets)

Memory is a structured, token-budgeted asset — not a probabilistic vector store for core operations.

```yaml
memory_compilation:
  tiers:
    CORE:
      budget_tokens: 500
      contents: "identity, mission, active sovereign"
      eviction: never
    WORKING:
      budget_tokens: 1000
      contents: "current task state, recent receipts, active context"
      eviction: LRU within tier
    EPISODIC:
      budget_tokens: 2000
      contents: "session history, decision轨迹, tool results"
      eviction: oldest first when budget exceeded
    ARCHIVAL:
      budget_tokens: 5000
      contents: "vault receipts, sealed documents, persistent memory"
      eviction: TTL-based (default 30 days)
  constraints:
    - "Model must never lose CORE identity due to context overflow"
    - "Vector search is a supplement, not the primary recall mechanism"
    - "All memory tiers must produce receipts on write"
```

